b'' b'(aaron swiers) writes:' b" can running a powerbook's battery completely flat have any" b' detrimental side effects (other than the pb not going i ask,' b' b' only two things i can think of.' b' although nicad (145,145,160,165c,170,180) batteries should be' b'completely' b" discharged about once a month, leadacid batteries shouldn't" b'ever be' b' completely discharged (well, maybe once in a while is okay).' b' b' this is a very common mis-conception dealing with ni-cad batteries. it' b'is' b' a good idea to completely discharge a ni-cad cell periodically. it is' b' not a good idea to completely discharge a ni-cad battery. the' b'difference' b' being that a cell is only one cell (nicad puts out volts) like a' b' rechargeable aaa, aa, c, or d. a battery is defined as more than one' b' cell volt, or for nicad equivalent). due to differences in the' b' individual cells of a battery, complete discharge can actually harm' b' a nicad battery more than help it overcome the "memory effect". the' b' most common problem is that over time an individual cell can develop' b' internal shorts, which will weaken other cells that are connected to' b' it, thus reducing the lifespan of your battery pack.' b'' b'etc....' b'' b'okay, naive question: how does one discharge a cell without discharging' b'the entire battery?' 